e Writes Africa and Canada shows how Laurence and her characters negotiate complex tensions between “self” and “nation,” and argues that Laurence’s African and Canadian writing demonstrates a divided Canadian subject who holds significant implications for both the individual and the country of Canada.Bringing together Laurence’s writing about Africa and Canada, Davis offers a unique contribution to the study of Canadian literature. The book is an original interpretation of Laurence’s work and reveals how she displaces the simple notion that Canada is a sum total of different cultures and conceives Canada as a mosaic that is in flux and constituted through continually changing social relations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfricans in literature. 0aDecolonization in literature. 0aNational characteristics, African, in literature. 0aNational characteristics, Canadian, in literature. 0aNationalism in literature. 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh  aCanada as postcolonial.  aCanadian literature.  aCanadian nationalism.  aMargaret Laurence's African writing.  aMargaret Laurence's Canadian writing.  aMargaret Laurence.  aWestern Canadian literature.  adecolonization in Canada.  adecolonization.  adivided subject in Canadian writing.  aprairie literature.  asettler-colony history in Canada.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112148440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771121484423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771121484/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978